(3) post-reduction usually stable — figure-of-8 brace 4-6 weeks;

(4) ถ้า unstable → open reduction + reconstruction (figure-of-8 graft of clavicle to manubrium, semi-tendinosus autograft);

(5) avoid K-wire/Steinmann pin fixation (catastrophic migration into mediastinum reported);

(6) post-op CXR + observation 24 hours;

(7) physical therapy after immobilization;

(8) high index suspicion — anterior SC more common (less dangerous) but posterior must be confirmed by CT chest with contrast
————————————————
Posterior SC dislocation: rare but vascular/airway emergency. CT chest + contrast diagnostic. Reduce in OR with CT surgery available. Posterior often stable after reduction. AVOID K-wires (migration into mediastinum fatal). Anterior SC dislocation much more common, less dangerous, often left reduced/conservative.

ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด)

APC II Open-Book Pelvic Fracture with Hemodynamic Instability:

(1) immediate pelvic binder (T-POD, sheet) at level of greater trochanters → reduces pelvic volume + tamponades venous bleeding (primary source 85%);

(2) ATLS resuscitation — massive transfusion protocol (1:1:1 PRBC:FFP:platelets), TXA within 3 hours;

(3) FAST/CT to identify other bleeding sources (abdominal, thoracic);

